    37	 From the Atari Productivity Forum
    38	 =================================
    39	
    40	
    41	 Myles Cohen, one of the regulars here on CompuServe, asks:
    42	
    43	 "Does anyone know how to diagnose and fix a cartridge port... It used
    44	 to work until I did something that involved my scanner... which caused
    45	 it to not work any more...
    46	
    47	 Now everything on the MEGASTE works normally...except the
    48	 fershlugginer cartridge port...
    49	
    50	 I've already asked this...but never got an answer...And no...I can't
    51	 take it to a repair shop...because I use it every day...and it works
    52	 beautifully except for the two progs that use the port...one of which
    53	 is Notator...even if I knew of a repair shop in my area...which I
    54	 don't..."
    55	
    56	 Sysop Bob Retelle tells Myles:
    57	
    58	 "What happened with the scanner when the cartridge port stopped
    59	 working..?
    60	
    61	 I'm not sure if the cartridge lines are buffered electrically or
    62	 not.. that would be a good place to start.
    63	
    64	 There's also the possibility that the actual cartridge connector has
    65	 been loosened from the motherboard traces.  It might be a good idea to
    66	 try resoldering the connections with a low-powered soldering pencil."
    67	
    68	 Myles fills Bob in:
    69	
    70	 "I don't know...but the scanner was the last thing I had plugged into
    71	 the port when it stopped working...
    72	
    73	 Not being a hardware person...I have no idea what that last sentence
    74	 means...nor how to go  about it..."
    75	
    76	 Bob counts off a couple of possibilities for Myles:
    77	
    78	 "If you remember the problems Brad has had with his ST, the trouble in
    79	 both cases turned out to be an IC chip that goes between the
    80	 sensitive internal cirtuitry of the computer and the "outside
    81	 world"...
    82	
    83	 The chip effectively "buffers" the computer from the static
    84	 electricity, random voltage spikes on the telephone line, and all
    85	 kinds of unfriendly influences like that.
    86	
    87	 In many cases, these "buffer chips" will give their "lives" to
    88	 protect the rest of the system from these things.  Replacing them is
    89	 generally a pretty easy operation, and the chips themselves are fairly
    90	 common and inexpensive.
    91	
    92	 It's almost like replacing a blown fuse.
    93	
    94	 Now the ones Brad had trouble with were on the MIDI port and the
    95	 RS-232 serial port..  I'm not sure if the cartridge port has similar
    96	 "buffers" or not... it would be good electrical design to have them,
    97	 but they do add to the cost of the computer.  (I'll see if I can trace
    98	 the lines on my 520 and try to tell if there's anything I can identify
    99	 as buffering on the cartridge port).
   100	
   101	 That's an electronic possibility... the other thing I mentioned is a
   102	 "mechanical" possibility.
   103	
   104	 In inserting and removing cartridges and other devices, there's a lot
   105	 of physical force applied to the joints where the actual cartridge
   106	 socket is soldered onto the computer's motherboard.  Over time, that
   107	 force can break the tiny solder bonds that make the electrical
   108	 connections.  Sometimes it will result in erratic operation as the
   109	 board flexes and causes the connections to open and close, and other
   110	 times it can just render the connector completely inoperative...
   111	 (this is a common problem with most motherboard mounted connectors
   112	 like joystick connectors and keyboard sockets).
   113	
   114	 As long as there isn't any serious damage to the motherboard itself,
   115	 the fix is to carefully re-solder the connections.
   116	
   117	 Either solution (assuming that's the problem) will require some
   118	 electronics expertise..  the buffer chips on the ST are all soldered
   119	 to the motherboard, so replacing one is not just a matter of unpluging
   120	 it from a socket.
   121	
   122	 If you know anyone who's done electronics repair, it would be fairly
   123	 simple for them to do for you... nothing is Atari specific, or
   124	 requiring any special info.  Any electronics repair shop could do the
   125	 re-soldering or chip replacement if it turns out that's the solution."
   126	
   127	 Myles gives us some more information about his predicament:
   128	
   129	 "There are new developments...
   130	
   131	 I've been on the phone with a distant...from me...electronix guru who
   132	 listened to my tale of woe and suggested that I should use a
   133	 multi-tester on the outside pins...first and last...of the cartridge
   134	 port on the MEGASTE to see if there was conductivity...my reading
   135	 showed zero...
   136	
   137	 He then told me that the MegaSTE's cartridge port is protected a 1/2
   138	 Amp microfuse narked F-121 and which can easily be found on the
   139	 motherboard very close to the port...that all I had to do was to test
   140	 it for conductivity...which if I got a zero reading needs to be
   141	 replaced...I got a zero reading...
   142	
   143	 Now all I have to do is find a 1/2 Amp microfuse to replace it...I
   144	 guess that Best Electonics is my best bet...
   145	
   146	 What a great diagnostician you turned out to be...Just look at the
   147	 line on the top of this message that I quote from your pevious note..."
   148	
   149	 Well Myles, good luck with your cartridge port problem... at one time or
   150	 another, every computer owner has to deal with problems like this.
   151	 Luckily, there are people like Bob Retelle to help the rest of us out.
   152	
   153	 Meanwhile, Elaine Eedson asks about a program to make using CompuServe
   154	 even easier:
   155	
   156	 "Could anyone give me any information about navigation programs for
   157	 Atari ST that are comparable to CIM.  I'm  looking for one that can be
   158	 used and act like CIM."
   159	
   160	 Jim Ness tells Elaine:
   161	
   162	 "There are no CIM equivalents for the ST.  CIM is a CompuServe
   163	 product, and CompuServe has only made PC and Mac versions available.
   164	
   165	 There also is no other similar program, in terms of navigating by
   166	 Point-and-Click methods.
   167	
   168	 There is QuickCIS, a true navigator program.  QuickCIS quickly
   169	 gathers all mail and messages for you, and then logs off.  You read it
   170	 all offline, and your replies can be posted on your next call.
   171	 QuickCIS can be found in Library 4 here."
   172	
   173	 Stefan Daystrom of Barefoot Software tells Elaine:
   174	
   175	 "CIM itself is only available in IBM/compatible and Mac versions.  If
   176	 you _really_ need something _just like_ CIM, the only way on the Atari
   177	 would be to run an IBM or Mac emulator (typically involving adding
   178	 hardware).
   179	
   180	 However, if you're paying for the use of your account, why spend time
   181	 online "live", with _whatever_ user interface, when you can use an
   182	 _automated_ navigator that'll log on, capture all the messages you're
   183	 interested in, log off, let you read them and reply to them at any
   184	 speed you want ("off the clock"), and then log on again for just a
   185	 minute or two to upload all your replies?  _That_ you can get for the
   186	 Atari with QuickCis.  (Also get QCMsg_II, an improved message reader
   187	 that works with QuickCis.  You _can_ you QuickCis by itself, but
   188	 you'll have a lot more flexibility in reading and replying to messages
   189	 if you use QCMsg_II with it.)
   190	
   191	 An automated navigator such as QuickCis will cut your connect time
   192	 with CompuServe _way_ down.  If you have enough (offline!) time, you
   193	 can then use that to expand to reading other areas of CompuServe that
   194	 you might not have been able to afford if always using it "live".
   195	 It'll also cut down the amount of time your phone line at home is tied
   196	 up with modem calls..."
   197	
   198	 Take it from me Elaine, QuickCis is the way to go!
   199	
   200	 Now for "something completely different" from Rob Rasmussen:
   201	
   202	 "My ST knows exactly what month/day/year and time it is even though I
   203	 no longer have my DeskCart or any other clock installed! At least
   204	 sometimes it does, right now for example. I have not set the clock in
   205	 the XCONTROL panel (I hardly ever do). I turned my computer and hard
   206	 drive on today (Megafile 60) and used the programs TouchUp, Prism
   207	 Paint, PicSwitch, QuickCIS, EdHAK, Hotwire, Maxifile and maybe a few
   208	 others. But nowhere did I set the time. When I noticed this the other
   209	 day I thought later I'd imagined it! DeskCart used to be my time
   210	 keeper, but I took it out a few months ago. The CALendar accessory
   211	 also displays the correct month, day and year. This is really odd! I
   212	 know some HD's have clocks - could it be retaining the time from when
   213	 I used to have DeskCart?  Somehow I don't think so but I have no other
   214	 ideas. How can this possibly be happening?!! <g>
   215	
   216	 Not that I'm complaining, I like not having to set the clock!"
   217	
   218	 Sysop Bob Retelle tells Rob:
   219	
   220	
   221	 "What kind of hard drive interface do you have..?
   222	
   223	 Some of them have clocks built-in as an additional feature.
   224	
   225	 The way these things work is that there has to be an external clock
   226	 of some kind that keeps regular daily time...  then when you boot up
   227	 your ST, some kind of AUTO folder program has to read the time of day
   228	 out of the external clock and put it into the ST's internal clock.
   229	
   230	 (For example, I have a clock chip that hides in an IC socket that's
   231	 installed under one of the TOS ROM chips in my ST... and an AUTO
   232	 folder program that reads the time into the ST's internal clock at
   233	 boot up..)
   234	
   235	 If you *don't* have anything in your AUTO folder that would read the
   236	 time out of something...  and you  *don't*  have anything that would
   237	 store the current time-of-day when your ST is turned off, maybe it's
   238	 time to take it in for its 50,000 mile exorcism..."
   239	
   240	 Rob tells Bob:
   241	
   242	 "I don't know about the hard drive interface - the Megafile just plugs
   243	 into the ST's hard drive port.
   244	
   245	 My auto programs are Shadow, Warp 9, Desk Manager, Spooler, Codekeys,
   246	 LGS, Hotwire and REGACC (for Lookit and Popit). Nothing I know of here
   247	 that would set the clock. I used to have Codehead's CLOCKSET in the
   248	 auto folder, but removed it when I took out DeskCart. Nowhere in the
   249	 Megafile manual did I see mention of a clock. Totally strange!"
   250	
   251	 Rob tells Bob about one interesting finding:
   252	
   253	 "I just did a cold boot and after all the auto programs loaded, I
   254	 checked the control panel, it was the wrong time (April, '89). I
   255	 loaded a few other programs to see where this odd (but rather nice)
   256	 time-keeping ability kicks in.  Using QuickCIS to call Compuserve is
   257	 what does it!!!!
   258	
   259	 I made a Normal call, captured an announcement, a few messages and lib
   260	 descriptions , then it logged off. The Xcontrol panel now displays
   261	 the correct date and time! 7:31 AM 11/16/93. Any files I save are
   262	 saved with the correct time. This is one bug that I consider a
   263	 feature, but who can explain it? I know Hotwire has a clock, but other
   264	 than calling CIS, nothing in my system could be retaining the time,
   265	 unless it's the ghost of DeskCart. It resented being replaced by the
   266	 scanner! Seriously, could CIS be setting my clock???"
   267	
   268	 Jon Sanford tells Rob:
   269	
   270	 "I think it is a feature of QuickCIS to set the system clock if it is
   271	 off by more than a certain ammount. Amazing what little bits of info
   272	 stick after reading a doc. 4 or 6 times...."
   273	
   274	 Rob re-reads the documentation and tells Jon:
   275	
   276	 "Well, you're right! There it is, kinda hidden in the docs  :^}. How
   277	 come I never knew about this? Maybe since I had the cartridge clock I
   278	 ignored this nifty feature."
   279	
   280	 Bob Retelle jumps in and adds:
   281	
   282	 "Wow..  I knew QuickCIS was a good program, but this is pretty
   283	 amazing..!
   284	
   285	 Er.. that is..  Of course.. just another special little advantage of
   286	 using CompuServe and QuickCIS.."
   287	
   288	 Jim Ness, the creator of of QuickCis, tells us:
   289	
   290	 "That was a feature requested by James Port.  He had a 520ST with no
   291	 clock, but wanted his .MSG files to have a real timestamp.  So, I
   292	 worked out a routine which compared the CIS time to the ST time, and
   293	 if it was off by more than 24 hours the clock would be set to CIS
   294	 time.
   295	
   296	 The 24 hour deadband was to account for someone calling in at approx.
   297	 midnight, or someone calling across a time zone or three."
   298	
   299	 While on the subject of calling up an on-line service, Stefan Daystrom
   300	 talks a bit about Alan Page's latest "baby", STORM:
   301	
   302	 "This isn't exactly a bug, but I thought I'd point out one other
   303	 problem with your 7-scanline med rez font besides readability (and it
   304	 bothers me _more_ than the readability <grin!>):
   305	
   306	 It makes Storm _slow_!!!!!
   307	
   308	 Well, what it does is it makes graphics accelerators like TurboST
   309	 which accelerate the stock fonts (in TurboST's case, 8x16, 8x8, and
   310	 6x6) unable to kick in, thus reducing Storm to standard GEM speeds
   311	 (which makes it seem real slow compared to Flash, which _does_ run at
   312	 TurboST speeds).
   313	
   314	 I recall reading a message where you said it you were planning to
   315	 handle this by a special emulation; does that mean it could not be
   316	 combined with other emulations?  (On the other hand, do I still need
   317	 to use Vidtex on CIS just to be able to download using CIS B
   318	 protocols, as I did in Flash, or can I just use the same TTY emulation
   319	 for CIS as I do for most BBSs I call?  If the latter, then I'm less
   320	 worried about it being a special TTY emulation that might use the 8X8
   321	 font in med rez...)"
   322	
   323	 Alan Page tells Stefan (and the rest of us):
   324	
   325	 "Actually, ALL my GEM text is done using custom code, no matter what
   326	 the font.  Much of the speed comes from trying to update large blocks,
   327	 rather than one character at a time. I thought it was rather fast,
   328	 actually.  CIS-B will work with any of the terminal emulations. I
   329	 normally log on to CIS with VT100. VIDTEX, however, does have an
   330	 option in the setup to switch to an 8 scanline font, with 21 lines in
   331	 medium rez. Select "Emulations" in the Settings menu, click on VIDTEX,
   332	 then click on Config. Warning: switching will erase the terminal
   333	 screen!  When I finally publish some source, people will be able to
   334	 customize the emulations extensively, including the ability to use
   335	 stock GEM text."
   336	
   337	 Stefan Daystrom tells Alan:
   338	
   339	 "Hm, I may have crossed circuits to jump to conclusions <grin / red
   340	 face>!
   341	
   342	 I don't have a 9600/14400 modem yet, so my sense of speed was not
   343	 based on _online_ speed (I've never seen it get behind relative to the
   344	 RD light on my modem, though it somehow _feels_ as if the pacing is
   345	 different than I'm used to!) as much as the speed with which the
   346	 window redraws when I flip between the capture buffer and terminal
   347	 windows.
   348	
   349	 But now that I look at it closer, the delay I see is probably just
   350	 the window drawing white behind the text, when it's topped, before the
   351	 text is drawn.
   352	
   353	 If I'm spoiled by even _greater_ speed, I realize now that's it's
   354	 from using QCMsg_II, which doesn't _need_ to redraw the window when I
   355	 flip between messages, _only_ the text.  So _obviously_ it's going to
   356	 be faster since it has less to do!
   357	
   358	 So you're right, the text is actually rather fast!  Sorry for making
   359	 assumptions..."
