   362	 From the Atari ST Arts Forum
   363	 ============================
   364	
   365	 Shawn Laughnin asks:
   366	
   367	 "Does the Atari require a special (i.e. Atari) joystick? I remember a
   368	 time you could buy a host of generic joysticks in chain stores. Its
   369	 been a while since I've noticed them ."
   370	
   371	 Sysop Bob Retelle tells Shawn:
   372	
   373	 "Yup, the "Atari Joystick" is a thing of the past, just like most
   374	 things Atari..
   375	
   376	 Used to be any joystick had to be "Atari compatible"... now they're
   377	 all Nintendo..  I wonder why that is..."
   378	
   379	 Master Sysop Ron Luks adds his own thoughts:
   380	
   381	 "Yes, the Atari uses a special joystick.  There used to be scads of
   382	 different brands of joysticks that worked on your atari (anything that
   383	 used to be compatible with the former industry standard Atari 2600
   384	 game machine and 8-bit computers) but these are becoming hard to
   385	 find."
   386	
   387	 Rob Rasmussen asks about "doing" graphics with some of the whiz-bang
   388	 graphics packages out there:
   389	
   390	 "...The positioning of 16 colors/shades of gray in the palette - that's
   391	 what I don't get. I'm used to coming from the other direction, where I
   392	 create a picture in Prism Paint, starting on a blank screen with
   393	 default colors in the palette which I can change. But how does a
   394	 scanned picture, or the software TouchUp, decide which position in the
   395	 palette a gray, black or white will be?  Even if I can use the feature
   396	 in Degas Elite and PP that maps the colors gradually between any two,
   397	 I'm still stuck with maybe 2 objects on the screen that I want to be
   398	 different colors, but they can't be because they're in the same
   399	 palette position. If I scan a picture lighter, there may be more
   400	 shades of gray and maybe certain pixels would be in different pal
   401	 positions, but the picture looks undefined with not enough detail.
   402	
   403	 I saved some scans as GIFs, others as PC1. I only have a color
   404	 monitor. When I try to load a GIF, I get a dialog with a 'gray scale'
   405	 button (using this makes everything too dark) and the dimensions of
   406	 the GIF which I find will not fit on the screen. Other scans will all
   407	 fit on the screen. It looks like the GIF really is just the top of the
   408	 scan - there is no way to scroll or print it. Any comments anyone?
   409	 This really is all a puzzle I hope to understand one day!"
   410	
   411	 Lee Seiler of Lexicore Software tells Rob:
   412	
   413	 "First install EP10 so you have access to 4096 colors, Next use Prism
   414	 Paint for the whole job. Hold the Alt Key when booting to get the
   415	 Grey scale Select dialog.  Then, when you load the color pic it will
   416	 auto Grey scale, the machine pallet will also have the correct Grey
   417	 scales auto set. Now when you save out as a PI file it will be in 8
   418	 grey scales including the required desk top reserved pallet."
   419	
   420	 Rob asks for clarification:
   421	
   422	 "I have an ST, not an STE. I thought I was limited to 512 colors. What
   423	 is EP10 and where can I get it? If I can get 4096 colors then this is
   424	 incredible!"
   425	
   426	 Lee explains to Rob:
   427	
   428	 "Many, many ST owners have installed the video shifter from JRI but
   429	 never realized that the 4096 colors were not always there, this is
   430	 also the case with the STE, Mega STE, and TT.  Many programs which
   431	 could use the 4096 don't, due to a little tic in the OS, EP10 deals
   432	 with this problem and while no difference is apparent, things like GIF
   433	 and Spectrum Images are much richer and look better because you see
   434	 "Better or More correctly matched colors" and with software that does
   435	 access the full 4096 you see a slight increase in speed, or so I am
   436	 told.
   437	
   438	 You get EP10 Free with all Lexicor purchases, we put it on all
   439	 current Utilitiy and resource disk sold with Lexicor products."
   440	
   441	 Rob tells Lee:
   442	
   443	 "I looked for EP10 on my Lexicor disks, but those are older programs,
   444	 so I guess it wasn't included. You mentioned the JRI video shifter -
   445	 is this required for an older ST to get 4096 colors? I would LOVE to
   446	 have more screen colors than 512 to choose from. Often I want colors
   447	 that are between 2 available ones that are right next to each other.
   448	
   449	 The picture I'm starting out with is a mono IMG and PI3. Is this what
   450	 I could gray scale before converting to low rez PNT or PI1 ? If I can
   451	 do this on an ST with EP10, then I'll need to get that or something
   452	 similar."
   453	
   454	 Lee explains exactly what is needed:
   455	
   456	 "Yes and no.
   457	
   458	 You do need the JRI hardware first, if you have the STE, the 4096 are
   459	 there but unaccesable. EP10 fixes the bug for all 4096 systems no
   460	 matter how it happens.  If you are using the PI3 you should be able to
   461	 load it into a grey scale Prism paint mode of at least 16 shades of
   462	 grey.
   463	
   464	 This then is saved as a Gif which can then be reloaded into a color
   465	 Gif which you can then reset from grey to color and save as color.
   466	
   467	 EP10 is in all our libs as far as I know, knock on Ringo's door and
   468	 ask him to point you at it or E-Mail it to you."
   469	
   470	 Mike Myers asks Sysop Ron Luks about converting Atari files over to
   471	 DOS (I know, I know, I've mentioned this a lot... but the question
   472	 keeps getting asked, so I guess that not everyone reads this column
   473	 all the time [and you know who you are]):
   474	
   475	 "Is there a program available which will allow the conversion of ATARI
   476	 ST .lzh files to IBM .gif files / .jpg files and back?  I have an IBM
   477	 and a friend has a ST.  We have looked in the forums under viewers,
   478	 utilities, and anything else we could think of."
   479	
   480	 Before Ron can answer, Sysop Bob Retelle tells Mike:
   481	
   482	 "There should be a conversion program that will run on an ST and
   483	 convert DEGAS format pictures to GIF, which your friend could display
   484	 on his IBM..
   485	
   486	 It's been a looong time since I remember seeing it, but I think its
   487	 filename was something like  CNV2GIF.   There should also be something
   488	 similar that will convert Spectrum 512 pictures to GIF format too, but
   489	 the name of that one eludes me at this moment.
   490	
   491	 As for converting the other way, there shouldn't be a need to convert
   492	 GIFs and JPGs, since we have some pretty good viewer programs for the
   493	 ST for those graphics formats."
   494	
   495	 Ron Luks tells Mike:
   496	
   497	 "LZH is a compression method.  GIF is a picture file format.
   498	
   499	 There is an LZH utility for the PC.  (LZH files are created/processed
   500	 witha utility called LHARC).  Think of LZH as another type of ARC or
   501	 ZIP files. GIF is a graphics picture format like TIFF, or PCX, etc.
   502	 One has nothing to do with the other.
   503	
   504	 I dont know of any JPEG utilities for the Atari ST."
   505	
   506	 Boris Molodyi jumps in and adds:
   507	
   508	 "As I recall, GEMVIEW loads JPEG files (and so you can save them in
   509	 different format). Also, Studio Photo from Compo can load JPEG pics."
   510	
